    39	## EARLY HISTORY
    40	In 1848, Kirchhoff (1) generalized Ohm's law to three dimensions, and
    41	noted an interesting fact. If the electric field is $E = -\nabla\phi$,
    42	the conductivity $\sigma(\mathbf{x})$, then when a steady state is
    43	reached the potential $\phi(\mathbf{x})$ must cause no accumulation of
    44	electric charge at any point:
    45	
    46	$$\nabla \cdot (\sigma \nabla \phi) = 0. \tag{1}$$
    47	
    48	But this is just the Euler-Lagrange equation stating that the rate of
    49	production of Joule heat in a volume V
    50	$$\int_V \sigma(\nabla\phi)^2 dV \tag{2}$$
    51	
    52	is stationary with respect to
    53	variations $\delta\phi(\mathbf{x})$ that vanish on the boundary of V.
    54	Thus the current distributes itself so as to dissipate the least
    55	possible heat for given voltages applied on its boundary. This is
    56	probably the first example of a steady nonequilibrium state determined
    57	by a variational principle.
