   305	## ONSAGER'S THEORY
   306	Irreversible thermodynamics had its historical origins in Thomson's
   307	analysis of the thermocouple in 1854. For the effect of transporting a
   308	charge q around the circuit, he assumed that one might apply Carnot's
   309	principle in the form $\sum Q_i/T_i=0$ to the reversible Peltier and
   310	Thomson heat effects even though irreversible heat conduction was also
   311	present.
   312	
   313	Indeed, unless something like this were true, there would be few real
   314	applications in which one could ever apply Carnot engine arguments with
   315	any confidence. His assumption went beyond the principles of
   316	thermostatics and yielded, for the interaction of heat flow and electric
   317	current, the first example of an "Onsager reciprocal relation."
   318	
   319	By 1931 many such relations had been noted, and Onsager (14) sought a
   320	general theoretical justification for them. His argument is still worth
   321	recalling because the formal relations survive, generalized and
   322	reinterpreted, in our present theory. We summarize it briefly, noting
   323	the four "serious" assumptions by Roman numerals and limiting comments
   324	to the square brackets.
